content.value_statement: An AI skill for Claude, Codex, and Claude Code
actual_capabilities: Search proteins by name, gene symbol, accession, or organism using natural language or structured queries
Retrieve protein sequences in FASTA, JSON, TSV, XML, or other formats
Map identifiers between UniProt and external databases (Ensembl, RefSeq, PDB, AlphaFoldDB)
Access protein annotations including GO terms, domains, and functional descriptions
Batch retrieve multiple protein entries efficiently
Query reviewed (Swiss-Prot) vs unreviewed (TrEMBL) protein data
Stream large protein datasets without pagination limits
Build custom queries with field-specific search syntax
Filter by sequence length, molecular mass, taxonomy, and other properties
limitations: ID mapping results are stored for only 7 days
Large queries may require pagination or streaming
TrEMBL entries are computational predictions, not manually reviewed
API rate limits apply for bulk operations
Some specialized databases may not be available for ID mapping
Complex boolean queries may have syntax limitations

best_practices: Use reviewed entries when possible by filtering with reviewed:true for Swiss-Prot (manually curated) entries
Specify format explicitly based on your needs (FASTA for sequences, TSV for tabular data, JSON for programmatic parsing)
Use field selection to only request needed fields, reducing bandwidth and processing time
Implement proper pagination for large result sets or use the stream endpoint for complete datasets
Cache frequently accessed data locally to minimize API calls and improve performance
Be respectful of API resources by implementing delays between large batch operations
Check data quality - TrEMBL entries are computational predictions while Swiss-Prot are manually reviewed
Use specific field searches (gene:, accession:, organism_name:) rather than generic text searches for better results
Validate accession numbers before retrieval - classic format is 6 characters, extended is 10 characters
anti_patterns: Don't use generic text searches without field qualifiers - they return too many irrelevant results
Don't retrieve all fields when you only need a few - this wastes bandwidth and processing time
Don't ignore the difference between Swiss-Prot (reviewed) and TrEMBL (unreviewed) entries
Don't hardcode URLs in your code - use the provided client or construct URLs programmatically
Don't make sequential rapid API calls without delays - implement rate limiting to avoid being blocked
Don't use outdated accession numbers - check for entry updates or replacements
Don't assume all proteins have complete annotations - some entries may have limited information
Don't use ID mapping for more than 100,000 IDs in a single job - split large mapping tasks

faq.question: What's the difference between Swiss-Prot and TrEMBL?
faq.answer: Swiss-Prot contains manually reviewed and curated protein sequences with high-quality annotations, while TrEMBL contains computationally predicted sequences awaiting manual review. Use 'reviewed:true' in queries to get only Swiss-Prot entries.

faq.question: How do I search for proteins from a specific organism?
faq.answer: Use the organism_name or organism_id fields. For example: 'organism_name:"Homo sapiens"' or 'organism_id:9606' for human proteins. You can also use 'taxonomy_name' or 'taxonomy_id' for broader taxonomic groups.

faq.question: What's the maximum number of results I can retrieve?
faq.answer: The search endpoint returns up to 500 results per page. For larger datasets, use pagination parameters or the stream endpoint which returns all results without limits. ID mapping has a limit of 100,000 IDs per job.

faq.question: How do I get protein sequences in FASTA format?
faq.answer: Use the format=fasta parameter in your search query, or retrieve specific entries by accession with .fasta extension: 'https://rest.uniprot.org/uniprotkb/{accession}.fasta'. You can also use the client script's get_protein() function.

faq.question: Can I map identifiers between UniProt and other databases?
faq.answer: Yes, use the ID mapping service at /idmapping/run endpoint. Supported databases include Ensembl, RefSeq, PDB, AlphaFoldDB, KEGG, and many more. See /references/id_mapping_databases.md for the complete list.
